NAME OF OUTSIDE REVIEWER: Vladimir D. Kravtsov, II, MD
5.7% abnormal CD56-positive/CD117-positive plasma cell population identified, monoclonal kappa.
Flow cytometry studies reveal an abnormal plasma cell population expressing bright
CD38 and having cytoplasmic kappa light chain restriction. The plasma cells aberrantly co-express CD56 and CD117, an
immunophenotype that has been associated with a more favorable prognosis in plasma cell neoplasia. The abnormal plasma
cells represent 5.7% of the total viable cells. Virtually no polyclonal plasma cells are present in the background These findings
are consistent with involvement by a plasma cell neoplasm. Of note, flow cytometry usually underestimates the percentage of
plasma cells in comparison with morphology. The B cells show no evidence of clonality or antigenic aberrancy. The T cells
show normal expression of the pan T-cell antigens and have a normal CD4:CD8 ratio. The NK cells account for 13.8° of the
total lymphocytes. Close clinical follow up is recommended.
Immunophenotyping by flow cytometry after erythroid lysis reveals that the plasma cells represent 5.7% of the total viable
cells. The plasma cells have a cytoplasmic kappa:lambda ratio of 1881 (normal 1-2) and show expression of bright CD38 and
CD138, and intermediate CD45. An approximately 64.8% subset of the plasma cells co-expresses aberrant CD56. An
approximately 82.2% subset of plasma cells co-expresses aberrant CD117. The plasma cells do not express any significant
CD19, CD20, or CD28. The lymphocytes consist of 2.6% B cells (CD19+), 83.6% T cells (CD3+), and 13.8% NK cells
(CD3-, CD56+). The T cells show normal expression of the pan T-cell antigens CD2, CD3, CD5, and CD7 and have a
CD4:CD8 ratio of 2.3 (Normal 1 - 4). The B cells have a kappa:lambda ratio of 1.1 (Normal 1-2), express bright CD20, without
significant expression of CD5 or CD10. Hematogones account for 0.85% of the CD19-positive B cells and 0.0056% of the total
white blood cells. Among 99547 events collected, 5647 plasma cells were identified and available for analysis. The specimen
integrity was sufficient to perform the study.

Considerable normocytic anemia, mild leukopenia, and marked thrombocytopenia.
Plasma cell myeloma involves approximately 50-60% of the cellular marrow space. There is interstitial plasmacytosis with
areas of monomorphic plasma cell infiltrates exceeding 1/2 of a high powered field in diameter. Flow cytometry confirms a
monotypic population of plasma cells. FISH studies for plasma cell myeloma will be performed as well as SGNGS testing.
Further followup is suggested as clinically indicated.
Complete blood count performed at PathGroup Laboratories. Direct evaluation of a peripheral blood smear reveals that
circulating leukocytes are accurately reflected in the numerical differential. Lymphocytes are heterogeneous without evidence
of monomorphic population. No circulating blasts are identified. Circulating platelet estimate is markedly decreased. Red blood
cells are normocytic without abnormal red cell morphology present. Red blood cells show no evidence of rouleaux formation.
